SIMPLE: nymph
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: nymph
<hw>nymph</hw> <pr>(n⟦icr⟧mf)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>nympha</ets> nymph, bride, young woman, Gr. <grk>ny`mfh</grk>: cf.
F. <ets>nymphe</ets>. Cf. <er>Nuptial</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Class. Myth.)</fld> <def>A goddess of the
mountains, forests, meadows, or waters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where were ye, <qex>nymphs</qex>, when the remorseless deep⟦br⟧
Closed o'er the head of your loved Lycidas?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A lovely young girl; a
maiden; a damsel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Nymph</qex>, in thy orisons⟦br⟧
Be all my sins remembered.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The pupa of an insect; a
chrysalis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of a subfamily
(<subfam>Najades</subfam>) of butterflies including the purples, the
fritillaries, the peacock butterfly, etc.; -- called also
<altname>naiad</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>nympha</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
